rise what Schleitwiler calls “imperialism’s racial justice.” This process could only be sustained through an ongoing training of perception in an aesthetics of racial terror, through rituals of racial and colonial violence that also provide the conditions for an elusive countertraining. With an innovative prose style, Strange Fruit of the Black Pacific pursues the poetic and ethical challenge of reading, or learning how to read, the black and Asian literatures that take form and flight within the fissures of imperialism’s racial justice. Through startling reinterpretations of such canonical writers as James Weldon Johnson, Nella Larsen, Toshio Mori, and Carlos Bulosan, alongside considerations of unexpected figures such as the musician Robert Johnson and the playwright Eulalie Spence, Schleitwiler seeks to reactivate the radical potential of the Afro-Asian imagination through graceful meditations on its representations of failure, loss, and overwhelming violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxMigrationsxHistory. 0aFilipino AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aFilipino AmericansxMigrationsxHistory. 0aImperialismxSocial aspectszPacific AreaxHistory. 0aJapanese AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aJapanese AmericansxMigrationsxHistory. 0aUnited StatesxInsular possessionsxRace relationsxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107289720 cprintz978147986469040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479851744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479851744/original  